Search your area for Direct Primary Care practices/doctors. If you‚Äôre lucky, you‚Äôll have some! It‚Äôs a general practitioner who doesn‚Äôt take insurance anyway; they operate with a monthly membership fee (usually $100-$200/person) ‚Äî for unlimited primary care visits, discounts on labs/prescriptions, etc. 

Membership fees are tax deductible when paid from an HSA. 

If you can have that plus a catastrophic plan, many people are better off than traditional insurance anyway. Worth investigating!! üíó

As a survivor of suicide, this is what I wish people understood about depression and Mentalhealth üßµ
It‚Äôs not as simple as ‚Äúcheck on your friends and family.‚Äù Depression is a fierce illness. When someone is deep in it, they will lie to themselves and to you.
Depression has stages. When it gets severe, people isolate, push loved ones away, and even sabotage relationships to make it easier to disappear. It‚Äôs not about who cared enough to reach out.
The person you see is not always the whole story. Depression can make people live double lives outwardly fine, but internally drowning.

The solution to "check on your friends and family" someone is unfair and not helpful. It almost implies that the person that was loss didn't have enough love and care. Depression requires professional care. Love helps, but love alone can't prevent suicide.

You can love someone and still not see the depth of their struggle. Let's focus on the root of the problem: depression‚Äîearly intervention, accessible mental health care, and breaking the shame around getting help.
I‚Äôm so sorry for your pain. I lost a son to suicide. Sometimes I‚Äôm haunted by the ‚Äúwhat should I have done to help him?‚Äù It‚Äôs so hard to lose a loved one to suicide

My brother died by suicide over 45 years ago and I‚Äôm hit by the loss almost every day. He was loved and cherished, but there was this one tragedy he could get over or make sense of. You outlined some good and useful points. Thank you for sharing and trusting your vulnerability with strangers. I believe you have or will save a life by sharing your truth üòå

As a Psychiatric Nurse Practitioner who just lost her 19-year-old son to suicide 6 months ago I can assure you we still don‚Äôt fully understand what depression does to an individual. 

I did so much to save my son yet he still died. He knew he had me to fight with him. He knew he was never alone and seemed to be making tremendous progress. 

I‚Äôll never stop fighting for a cure for this horrible disease. I owe it to my son and countless others who suffer in silence.

Obviously this won‚Äôt work for *everyone* but birth control can be terrible and I went back to therapy and continued to do the work.
